	   <tr><td colspan=2><i>What is a nice way to explain to one's group that bard songs taunt a LOT without dying first?</i>Tell the group (in your own words) "Hey guys, My songs are a serious taunt to the MOBS, cause Im so freaking awesome and do so much for the party, they cant help but wanna kill me.  Healers, please keep an eye on me, Taunters, please be aware that although I dual wield and wear plate, I'm not a tank.<br>One other thing Gual, consider your song selection for every fight.  Hymn of restoration really doesnt do a whole lot during battles, although I twist in in melee myself most times.  But If I find myself in a group that cant seem to keep the mobs off me, I will only sing Hymn in downtime, with the lute out.  Change your song line up to meet both the targets you are fighing and the party you are fighting with.<br><br><i> Also, should I tell the tanks to each target different mobs or to assist off me?</i><br>In most cases, the majority of the party should be on a single mob, nuking and fighting it.  Unless you are the group leader or puller, you shouldn't really be determining the main target. Let the Enchanters control the crowd if you have one, if not, let the group leader dictate the main target.   <br>In melee, I always try to keep an eye on the casters, so I can melee the mobs off them if I have too.  Remember, we should let ourselves get too committed to one target or type of fighting.  Our strength lies in our ability to adjust to different situations and make OTHER party members more effective.<br>&nbsp;<br>Sapper Diesalot, At Deaths Door.  "Chuck Berry cant twist this good!"</td></tr>
